SIMPLE: perfume
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Perfume
<hw>Per*fume"</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r*f⟦umac⟧m")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Perfumed</conjf>
<pr>(p⟦etil⟧r*f⟦umac⟧md")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Perfuming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>parfumer</ets> (cf.
Sp. <ets>perfumar</ets>); <ets>par</ets> (see <er>Par</er>) +
<ets>fumer</ets> to smoke, L. <ets>fumare</ets>, fr. <ets>fumus</ets>
smoke. See <er>Fume</er>.]</ety> <def>To fill or impregnate with a
perfume; to scent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Carmel's flowery top <qex>perfumes</qex> the skies.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perfume</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Perfume
<hw>Per"fume</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r"f⟦umac⟧m or p⟦etil⟧r*f⟦umac⟧m";
277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>parfum</ets>; cf. Sp.
<ets>perfume</ets>. See <er>Perfume</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The scent, odor, or odoriferous particles emitted from
a sweet-smelling substance; a pleasant odor; fragrance; aroma.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No rich <qex>perfumes</qex> refresh the fruitful
<qex>field</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A substance that emits an agreeable odor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And thou shalt make it a <qex>perfume</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxx.
35.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>perfumed</ent>⟦br⟧
